def load_time_series_data(filepath, time_column, y_column, delimiter=',', date_format=None, resample_freq=None):
    print(f"Loading: {filepath}")
    try:
        df = pd.read_csv(filepath, sep=delimiter, engine='python')
        df.columns = df.columns.str.strip()
            
        df[time_column] = pd.to_datetime(df[time_column], format=date_format)
        df = df.set_index(time_column).sort_index()
        
        plot_data = df[[y_column]].copy() 

        plot_data[y_column] = pd.to_numeric(plot_data[y_column], errors='coerce')

        if resample_freq:
            plot_data = plot_data.resample(resample_freq).mean()
            print(f"Resampled to {resample_freq} frequency.")
        
        print(f"Successfully loaded and processed {filepath}.\n")
        return plot_data

    except FileNotFoundError:
        print(f"File not found: {filepath}\n")
        return Noneths
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred during loading: {e}\n")
        return None

def load_and_melt_wide_data(filepath, time_column, resample_freq=None):
    print(f"Loading and melting: {filepath}")
    df = pd.read_csv(filepath, sep=',', engine='python')
    df.columns = df.columns.str.strip()
    
    df[time_column] = pd.to_datetime(df[time_column])
    df = df.sort_values(by=time_column)
    
    df_long = df.melt(
        id_vars=[time_column],
        var_name='unique_id',
        value_name='y'
    )
    
    df_long['y'] = pd.to_numeric(
        df_long['y'],
        errors='coerce'
    )
    df_long = df_long.dropna()
    
    df_long = df_long.rename(
        columns={time_column: 'ds'}
    )
    
    if resample_freq:
        df_long = df_long.set_index('ds')
        df_long = df_long.groupby('unique_id').resample(resample_freq).mean()
        df_long = df_long.reset_index() 

    print("Successfully loaded and melted data.\n")
    return df_long

def time_plots(df, y_column, title):
    with plt.style.context('grayscale'):
        plt.figure(figsize=(15,6))
        df[y_column].plot()
        
        plt.title(title,fontsize=16)
        plt.xlabel("Time")
        plt.ylabel(y_column)
        plt.grid(True, which='both', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5)
        plt.show()

def plot_all_series(df, title, x_col='ds', y_col='y', group_col='unique_id'):
    print(f"Plotting all series: {title}")
    if df is None:
        print("DataFrame is None, cannot plot.\n")
        return
    with plt.style.context('grayscale'):
        g = sns.relplot(
            data=df,
            x=x_col,
            y=y_col,
            col=group_col, 
            col_wrap=4,    
            kind='line',
            height=2.5,
            aspect=1.5,
            facet_kws={'sharey': False}
        )
        g.fig.suptitle(title, y=1.03, fontsize=16)
        g.set_axis_labels("Time", "Value")
        plt.show()

def seasonal_plot(df, y_column, title, period_unit):
        
    print(f"Seasonal plot: {title}")
    
    df_plot = df.copy()
    
    if period_unit == 'month':
        df_plot['group'] = df_plot.index.year
        df_plot['period'] = df_plot.index.month
        x_label = 'Month'
        hue_label = 'Year'
        palette = 'gist_rainbow' 
    
    elif period_unit == 'dayofweek':
        # Taking a sample of last n weeks
        df_plot = df_plot.last('52W') 
        df_plot['group'] = df_plot.index.to_period('W')
        df_plot['period'] = df_plot.index.dayofweek
        x_label = 'Day of week (0=Mon, 6=Sun)'
        hue_label = 'Week'
        palette = 'gist_rainbow' 
    
    elif period_unit == 'hour':
        # Taking a sample of last n days
        df_plot = df_plot.last('7D') 
        df_plot['group'] = df_plot.index.date
        df_plot['period'] = df_plot.index.hour
        x_label = 'Hour of day'
        hue_label = 'Day'
        palette = 'gist_rainbow'
        
    else:
        print(f"Error: period_unit '{period_unit}' not supported.")
        return

    with plt.style.context('grayscale'):
        plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
        ax = sns.lineplot(
            data=df_plot, 
            x='period', 
            y=y_column, 
            hue='group', 
            palette=palette,
            legend='full' if period_unit == 'month' else False #if not cluttered
        )
        plt.title(title, fontsize=16)
        plt.xlabel(x_label)
        plt.ylabel(y_column)
        
        if period_unit == 'month':
            # Placing the legend outside the plot
            ax.legend(title=hue_label, bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
        
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

def plot_seasonal_subseries(df, y_column, title, period_unit):   
    print(f"Plotting seasonal subseries: {title}")
    
    try:
        df_plot = df.copy()
        
        if period_unit == 'month':
            df_plot['group'] = df_plot.index.month_name()
            df_plot['period'] = df_plot.index.year
            x_label = 'Year'
            col_order = list(month_name)[1:] 
            col_wrap = 4
        
        elif period_unit == 'dayofweek':
            df_plot['group'] = df_plot.index.day_name()
            df_plot['period'] = df_plot.index.year 
            x_label = 'Year'
            col_order = list(day_name) 
            col_wrap = 4
            
        else:
            print(f"Error: period_unit '{period_unit}' not supported for subseries plot.")
            return

        g = sns.FacetGrid(
            df_plot, 
            col='group', 
            col_wrap=col_wrap, 
            col_order=col_order,
            height=3, 
            aspect=1.5,
            sharey=True
        )
        
        g.map(sns.lineplot, 'period', y_column) 
        
        g.map(plt.axhline, y=df_plot.groupby('group')[y_column].mean().mean(), color='gray', linestyle='--')
        
        g.fig.suptitle(title, y=1.03, fontsize=16)
        g.set_axis_labels(x_label, "Value")
        g.set_titles("{col_name}")
        
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()
        
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred during plotting: {e}\n")
In [8]:
def plot_lag(df, y_column, title, lags): 
    print(f"Plotting lag plots: {title}")
    
    try:
        n_lags = len(lags)
        n_cols = int(np.ceil(np.sqrt(n_lags)))
        n_rows = int(np.ceil(n_lags / n_cols))
        
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(n_rows, n_cols, figsize=(4 * n_cols, 4 * n_rows), sharex=True, sharey=True)
        axes_flat = axes.flatten()
        
        for i, lag in enumerate(lags):
            ax = axes_flat[i]
            lag_plot(df[y_column], lag=lag, ax=ax, alpha=0.5)
            ax.set_title(f'Lag {lag}')
            ax.set_xlabel('y(t)')
            ax.set_ylabel(f'y(t+{lag})')
        
        for i in range(n_lags, len(axes_flat)):
            axes_flat[i].axis('off')
            
        fig.suptitle(title, y=1.02, fontsize=16)
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred during plotting: {e}\n")

def plot_seasonal_lag(df, y_column, title, lags, period_unit): 
    print(f"Plotting seasonal lag plots: {title}")
    
    try:
        plot_df = pd.DataFrame({'y': df[y_column]})
        
        if period_unit == 'month':
            month_order = list(month_name)[1:]
            plot_df['Season'] = df.index.month_name()
            plot_df['Season'] = pd.Categorical(plot_df['Season'], categories=month_order, ordered=True)
            hue_order = month_order
            
        elif period_unit == 'dayofweek': 
            day_order = list(day_name)
            plot_df['Season'] = df.index.day_name()
            plot_df['Season'] = pd.Categorical(plot_df['Season'], categories=day_order, ordered=True)
            hue_order = day_order
        elif period_unit == 'quarter': 
            quarter_order = ['Q1', 'Q2', 'Q3', 'Q4']
            plot_df['Season'] = 'Q' + df.index.quarter.astype(str)
            plot_df['Season'] = pd.Categorical(plot_df['Season'], categories=quarter_order, ordered=True)
            hue_order = quarter_order            
        else:
            print(f"Error: period_unit '{period_unit}' not supported.")
            return

        n_lags = len(lags)
        n_cols = int(np.ceil(np.sqrt(n_lags)))
        n_rows = int(np.ceil(n_lags / n_cols))
        
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(n_rows, n_cols, figsize=(5 * n_cols, 5 * n_rows), sharex=True, sharey=True)
        axes_flat = axes.flatten()
        
        for i, lag in enumerate(lags):
            ax = axes_flat[i]
            
            temp_df = plot_df.copy()
            temp_df[f'y_lag_{lag}'] = temp_df['y'].shift(lag)
            temp_df = temp_df.dropna() 

            sns.scatterplot(
                data=temp_df, 
                x='y', 
                y=f'y_lag_{lag}', 
                hue='Season',
                hue_order=hue_order,
                palette='gist_rainbow',
                alpha=0.7,
                ax=ax
            )
            
            min_val = min(temp_df['y'].min(), temp_df[f'y_lag_{lag}'].min())
            max_val = max(temp_df['y'].max(), temp_df[f'y_lag_{lag}'].max())
            ax.plot([min_val, max_val], [min_val, max_val], color='gray', linestyle='--')
            
            ax.set_title(f'Lag {lag}')
            ax.set_xlabel('y(t)')
            ax.set_ylabel(f'y(t+{lag})')
            ax.legend_.remove() 

        handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
        fig.legend(handles, labels, title='Season', bbox_to_anchor=(1.02, 0.95), loc='upper left')
        
        for i in range(n_lags, len(axes_flat)):
            axes_flat[i].axis('off')
            
        fig.suptitle(title, y=1.02, fontsize=16)
        plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 0.9, 1]) 
        plt.show()

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred during plotting: {e}\n")

def plot_autocorrelation(df, y_column, title, lags):
    print(f"Plotting ACF: {title}")
    
    try:
        plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
        ax = plt.gca() 
        
        plot_acf(df[y_column].dropna(), lags=lags, ax=ax)
        
        ax.set_title(title, fontsize=16)
        ax.set_xlabel('Lag')
        ax.set_ylabel('Autocorrelation')
        plt.show()

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred during plotting: {e}\n")

Seasonal plot: UK air passengers

Plotting seasonal subseries: UK air passengers subseries by month

On the first graph here we can see that again we have seasonality, which seems to have highest numbers in July and August and a sharp decline in 2020 (Covid-19). From the second plot we see that people seem to travel more in I would call it "summer part of the year" from April to October. Also we see that in April 2010 there is a sharp decline - because of volcano eruption in Iceland atmosphere was too bad. Also the sharp dip in December 2010 was caused by severe, widespread snow and record-low temperatures across the UK and Europe. And there was an economic crisis in 2007-2009, which is also seen on the graphs.

Plotting lag plots: UK air passengers lag plots

Plotting ACF: UK air passengers ACF

Passengers lag plots show that one month's passenger count is a very strong predictor of the next month's count. The relationship weakens at intermediate lags (like 6 and 9), but then becomes strong and tight again at lag 12. Passengers ACF shows that the lags start very high and decay very slowly. We see a strong trend, meaning the series is non-stationary.

In [35]:
plot_lag(
    aep_daily_df, 
    'AEP_MW', 
    'AEP Daily Energy Lag Plots',
    lags=[1, 2, 7, 30] 
)

plot_autocorrelation(
    aep_daily_df, 
    'AEP_MW', 
    'AEP Daily Energy ACF', 
    lags=52 
)

Plotting lag plots: AEP Daily Energy Lag Plots

Plotting ACF: AEP Daily Energy ACF

First plot shows that the data has strong short-term persistence and a powerful weekly seasonal pattern. Lag 1 - tight, diagonal cloud shows a strong positive correlation meaning yesterday's energy consumption is a very good predictor of today's. Lag 7 - correlation becomes strong and tight again. Monday's consumption is highly correlated with the previous Monday's. Lags 2 and 30 - relationship at lags is much weaker, with the points forming a "fatter," more scattered cloud.

Second ACF plot provides shows strong weekly seasonality. The autocorrelation at lag 1 is extremely high (around 0.9) and all lags remain significant (outside the blue band). This confirms the series is not random and is highly persistent. We also see a repeating "wave" pattern. The spikes are highest at Lags 7, 14, 21, 28 and 35 (all multiples of 7). This is the statistical signature of a strong 7-day (weekly) seasonal pattern.
